"""
era_hermon_rebellion.py -- The Second Rebellion: Hermon (Chapters 3-4)

The second rebellion is independent of the first. Two hundred Watchers
descended on Mount Hermon (from the root ch-r-m, 'devoted to destruction'),
bound themselves by oath, and crossed the divine boundary by taking human
wives. Genesis 6:1-4 records the crossing; 1 Enoch 6-16 provides the
detailed account. The Sethite interpretation -- that 'sons of God' means
the line of Seth -- was introduced in the 3rd century AD by Julius Africanus
and has zero grounding in the Hebrew text. bene ha-elohim means divine
beings everywhere it appears in the OT (Job 1:6, 2:1, 38:7).

The offspring were the Nephilim -- fallen ones (n-p-l). According to
1 Enoch 15:8-10, when the Nephilim were destroyed, their disembodied
spirits became the demons that roam the earth. Four categories of
spiritual beings result from this framework: imprisoned Watchers,
territorial princes (Deut 32:8), demons (disembodied Nephilim),
and Satan himself.
"""

